#include <iostream>
using namespace std;
int main() 
{
    int num = 100;
    num *= 1000000;
    std::cout << num << std::endl;
    return 0;
}
</pre>
    <h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Description">Description</span></h3>
    <p id="description">All of these programs demonstrate, through use of the word
      template, a technique for using new C++ libraries, in a completely different
      way than any of the previous three examples.</p>
    <p id="description">Since C++11, there are two ways to do
      this. One is to use one of the <a
        href="/wiki/C%2B%2B11_libraries#Standard_template_library">standard template
        library</a> containers (namely, <span style="font-family: monospace"
        >std::string</span> and <span style="font-family: monospace"
        >std::vector</span>), and the other way is to use the
      <a href="/wiki/C%2B%2B14_(C%2B%2B_2011)#std::format">"modern" library</a>
      which is included with the C++14 standard.  The previous programs, which
      were done with the standard template library, use the simple string class
      (e.g., "<span style="font-family: monospace">std::string num =
        "hi there!");</span>") and the following new method of initializing
      a vector: <span style="font-family: monospace"
        >num.push_back('!');</span><br />
    </p>
    <p id="description">Most modern programs, however, are done
      "the old way". The following program, which is semantically equivalent to
      the previous example using new standard features, makes use of the
      <a href="/wiki/C%2B%2B_Standard_Library">C++ standard library</a>
      to print an English message: </p>
    <pre>
#include &lt;iostream&gt;
#include &lt;string&gt;
#include &lt;iomanip&gt;
using namespace std;
int main() 
{
    string x = "hi there!";
    cout.setf(ios::left, ios::adjustfield);</pre>
    <pre>#if CPLUSPLUS &gt; 11
    cout.setf(ios::showpos);</pre>
    <p>cout.setf() is a function in the standard template library
    which is used to set options for numeric output from the standard library. The
      output will be printed with no "0x" prefix when num is set to
      -12345678901234.  However, it
      would be difficult to keep adding this in each time. Instead, what
      we're doing here is setting the options in one place so later we write
      <span style="font-family: monospace">-12345678901234</span> and then the
      library function will do the work of formatting the output. It sets 0x as the
      prefix, sets left justification (prints the number off to the right) and
      set the showpos (prefixed sign).</p>
    <p>The second line of code was
      added to show how to set a new flag on the standard library. If
      CPLUSPLUS&gt;11 is defined, then the second line of code will be executed.
      If CPLUSPLUS&gt;11 is defined, a
      new flag <span style="font-family: monospace">std::ios::showpos</span> is
      set so that the library will print a +'ed prefix sign when num is set
      to -12345678901234.</p>
    <pre>
    cout.setf(ios::showbase, ios::basefield);
    cout &lt;&lt; -12345678901234 &lt;&lt; endl;
</pre>
    <p>In C++, we've used
      a "<span style